ometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Maltravers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Matravers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Matravers","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Mautravert in Chérencé-le-Héron (Manche)."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cambodian: written អ៊ីវ, unexplained. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>IV</i> (meaning ‘the fourth’ of the four bearers of the name) may also be counted as a surname <i>Iv</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":13,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":22,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Giffard de Maltravers IV was born in 1202, in Dorset, England as the son of John de Maltravers II. He married Mrs. John Giffard de Malttrvers IV in 1236, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1257, in Dorchester, Dorset, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1202–1257":"1202–1257","1205–1248":"1205–1248","1208–1257":"1208–1257","1212–Male":"1212–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1206–1276":"1206–1276","1238–1297":"1238–1297","1179–1262":"1179–1262","1297":"1297","1262":"1262","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1248":"1248","1236":"1236","1202":"1202","1257":"1257","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1212":"1212","1276":"1276","1208":"1208","Lytchett Matravers, Dorset, England":"Lytchett Matravers, Dorset, England","England":"England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fi":{"1202–1257":"1202–1257","1205–1248":"1205–1248","1208–1257":"1208–1257","1212–Male":"1212–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1206–1276":"1206–1276","1238–1297":"1238–1297","1179–1262":"1179–1262","1297":"1297","1262":"1262","1206":"1206","1238":"1238","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1248":"1248","1236":"1236","1202":"1202","1257":"1257","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1212":"1212","1276":"1276","1208":"1208","Lytchett Matravers, Dorset, England":"Lytchett Matravers, Dorset, England","England":"England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England","Dorset, Engla